\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study of our genes has uncovered a complex world of DNA binding proteins
 that interact to control and regulate gene expression.
 From DNA sequencing technology the genes that code for the proteins were
 found, but the rest of the genome remained largely a mystery.
 The regulatory functions are now being understood by profiling these DNA-protei
n interactions such as transcription factors and histone modifications that
 make gene transcription possible.
 New high throughput sequencing technology, or next-generation sequencing,
 has been applied to for these expanded the scope of gene regulatory study
 by providing a whole-genome view of gene regulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent studies have tried understand gene regulation by comparing different
 experiments across related species to determine how the binding sites vary.
 These studies have compared the transcription factor binding sites from
 mouse to human 
