\begin_layout Subsection
Processing of data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used MACS to identify peaks in each dataset.
 We also used a peak-centric approach and seperated the peak list into groups
 of overlapping and non-overlapping peaks from each experiment.
 The output from MACS in wiggle file format is used as the number of reads
 in non-overlapping bins p.
 The binned reads were combined all experiments into a single data table
 using a familiar databases algorithm called an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inner-join
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to match all read positions across all experiments.
 We also explored using an outer-join to include data for genome positions
 where zero reads aligned, however, this instead of filling zero for these
 positions we called these values missing.
 Then, the read values for these regions were imputed across nearby positions.
 This approach creates problems and creates striping of the data (Figure
 6).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting table of reads is large containing at 4-byte numeric over
 the whole genome divided into bins for each experiment.
 We used approximatelly 118mb for this table for the yeast ChIP-seq experiments
 we ysed (genome size 1.2*10^7bp, bin size n=10bp).
 Clearly, the dataset could become unmanageable for limited-memory environments
 if a larger genome was being processed or if a larger cohort was studied.
 We used a design pattern for data analysis called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

split-apply-combine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to break up the data for processing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wickham_split-apply-combine_2011"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Split-apply-combine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is similar to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

map-reduce
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 design pattern for parallel computing environments that can subdivide tasks
 amoungst workers, and it is also useful where the data can be split logically
 across a factor.
 In our case the read counts are split by chromosomes into different data
 frames to apply processing to read counts.
 The data can be split into more frames by cutting the table across ranges
 or other factors also, but for our application, it was easiest to split
 across chromosomes and apply functions without worrying about matching
 the chromosome features of the peaks different experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We mapped reads into bins for the whole-genome and looked for significant
 differences between ChIP-seq experiments using statistical tests.
 We used our algorithm to adjust for the differences that were identified
 on the basis of peak callers by for similar binding sites.
 This approach is significantly different from other approaches because
 it assumes that the distribution of the reads can be shown to be diffential
 via hypothesis testing.
 Other algorithms only find overlapping peaks and find differential peaks
 according to p-values.
 Additionally, we make strong assumptions about the data by using the binned
 reads, and performing the statistics on these bins assumes that they are
 independant.
 This is not a entirely valid because the aligned reads can overlap bins.
\end_layout

